–1430","1422–1460":"1422–1460","1424–1497":"1424–1497","1434–1459":"1434–1459","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1424":"1424","1434":"1434","1422":"1422","1497":"1497","1420":"1420","1430":"1430","1418":"1418","after 1420":"after 1420","Lewynesmede, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Shaw","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>s(c)hawe</i>, <i>s(c)haghe</i> ‘small wood, grove, thicket’ (Old English <i>sceaga</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a small wood, or habitational, for someone from any of the many places so named. <i>Shaw</i> and <i>Shawe</i> are most frequent in Lancashire and Yorkshire, where Shaw in Oldham (Lancashire) may be a principal source of the surname. The English and Lowland Scottish surname was also established in Ireland in the 17th century.","Scottish: shortened form of various surnames from the Gaelic personal name <i>Sitheach</i>, derived from <i>sithech</i> ‘wolf’.","Irish (Down and Antrim): adopted for <b>Ó Síthigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’. Compare   Sheehy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Show","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cumberland): probably a variant of   Shaw  , perhaps representing a blend in Middle English of Old English <i>sceaga</i> and Old Norse <i>skógr</i>, both meaning ‘wood’.","Perhaps an Americanized form of German   Schau  ."]},{"name":"Sheehy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Aisling, Brigid, Declan, Egan, Eoin, Finbar, Ronan.","Irish (Limerick and Kerry): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Síthigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Sítheach</i>’, or <b>Mac Síthigh</b> ‘son of <i>Sítheach</i>’, a form of the Irish personal name <i>Síodhach</i> ‘peaceful’, from the adjective <i>sítheach</i> ‘peaceful’ or ‘other worldly’ (see   Sheehan  ). The noun <i>síth</i>, from which this adjective derives, means basically ‘settlement’, hence both ‘peace’ and ‘place inhabited by other world beings’. This name was established in Ireland from the early 14th century, when a branch of the Scottish McDonnells, descended from <i>Sítheach</i>, great-grandson of Domhnaill, settled in the country."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Shaw was born in 1385, in Gloucestershire, England, her father, Shaw, was 26 and her mother, Mrs Shaw, was 26. She married Edward Lugg in 1418, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died after 1420, in her hometown."},"et":{"1385–after 1420":"1385–pärast 1420","1385–1420":"1385–1420","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1422–1460":"1422–1460","1424–1497":"1424–1497","1434–1459":"1434–1459","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1385":"1385","1460":"1460","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","1459":"1459","1424":"1424","1434":"143